The Haworth form of monosaccharides are classified as $\alpha$ or $\beta$ depending on the orientation of a single OH group: the OH group of the C atoms directly connected to the O atom in the cycle. If this OH groups points down we call this $\alpha$ and if its points up we call the structure as $\beta$ . Here some examples:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular*}{1\textwidth}{@{\extracolsep{\fill}}>{\centering}m{0.36\textwidth}>{\centering}m{0.27\textwidth}>{\centering}m{0.27\textwidth}}
\setatomsep{2.5em}\glucose[model=haworth,ring, anomer = alpha, color={anomerH}{orange}, color={anomerO}{orange}, color={ringO}{red}]&
\setatomsep{2.5em}\glucose[model=haworth,ring, anomer = beta, color={anomerH}{orange}, color={anomerO}{orange}, color={ringO}{red}]
\tabularnewline\addlinespace
\textcolor{blue}{$\alpha$-Glucose} & \textcolor{blue}{$\beta$-Glucose} \tabularnewline
\end{tabular*}\end{center}
